WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.817 --> 00:00:03.150
IRENE NOKAN: Well, hi, everyone.

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:05.210
Thank you for joining us today.

00:00:05.210 --> 00:00:07.510
My name is Irene
[? Nokan ?], and I

00:00:07.510 --> 00:00:10.960
am on the large customer sales
team out of San Francisco.

00:00:10.960 --> 00:00:15.140
I'm here today to introduce
chef Jason Halverson, formerly

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.170
the sous chef of Michael Mina.

00:00:17.170 --> 00:00:21.250
He is now the executive chef at
two San Francisco restaurants,

00:00:21.250 --> 00:00:25.690
Stones Throw in Russian Hill
and Trestle in Jackson Square.

00:00:25.690 --> 00:00:28.350
So please join me in
giving him a warm welcome.

00:00:28.350 --> 00:00:29.580
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:32.560
JASON HALVERSON: Thank you.

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:33.951
Thank you, thank you.

00:00:33.951 --> 00:00:34.450
Welcome.

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:35.825
Thank you for having us.

00:00:35.825 --> 00:00:38.540
It's super exciting.

00:00:38.540 --> 00:00:40.870
We're going to
make a pasta dish.

00:00:40.870 --> 00:00:44.080
Pasta really makes me happy.

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:49.480
It's a fun dish that really just
includes things that I like.

00:00:49.480 --> 00:00:51.890
And that's what's fun about
cooking for me, where you can

00:00:51.890 --> 00:00:52.890
include things that you like.

00:00:52.890 --> 00:00:54.660
If you like something,
you add more of it.

00:00:54.660 --> 00:00:56.160
If you don't like
something, keep it

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.110
out of there, which
makes it really fun.

00:00:58.110 --> 00:01:00.630
So what we're making is
a squid ink coquille.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.540
So coquille being the
shape of the pasta.

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.870
Squid ink being the
base or the flavor

00:01:05.870 --> 00:01:08.470
or the coloring of
what we're making.

00:01:08.470 --> 00:01:10.510
But to start we're
going to make the sauce.

00:01:10.510 --> 00:01:14.800
So the sauce itself is a
shellfish and caper sauce.

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:16.430
It's slightly spicy.

00:01:16.430 --> 00:01:18.110
The whole dish is
slightly spicy.

00:01:18.110 --> 00:01:19.630
There's a lot of acid.

00:01:19.630 --> 00:01:23.900
It's really, slightly rich,
which makes it a lot of fun.

00:01:23.900 --> 00:01:31.940
So to start in a pan, one
thing that we've done already

00:01:31.940 --> 00:01:33.400
is we've cut off
mussels and clams.

00:01:33.400 --> 00:01:36.610
If anybody hasn't ever cooked
mussels and clams, what

00:01:36.610 --> 00:01:38.650
we really did is we're
using it for the juice.

00:01:38.650 --> 00:01:41.200
And we're going to use the
clams and mussels later.

00:01:41.200 --> 00:01:44.330
But basically we had
a pan get really hot.

00:01:44.330 --> 00:01:47.330
We added the mussels and
the clams, covered them

00:01:47.330 --> 00:01:49.260
in white wine, covered
the pot, and what

00:01:49.260 --> 00:01:52.240
happens is they'll
steam opened letting out

00:01:52.240 --> 00:01:58.290
a lot of their liquid, which
is a great base for a sauce.

00:01:58.290 --> 00:02:01.910
Which you'll see how we
use it here in a second.

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:07.330
So trying to figure out how
to use this fancy stove.

00:02:07.330 --> 00:02:11.640
So what we have-- a smaller
pot, a little bit of oil.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:13.620
What we're going to do
is to the base of this,

00:02:13.620 --> 00:02:15.036
start by sweating
out some onions.

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:22.450
We're going to try to
make these translucent.

00:02:22.450 --> 00:02:24.940
You'll see, I guess in
my style of cooking,

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:27.350
onions are used as a
base for a lot of things.

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:29.320
It's just a great foundation.

00:02:29.320 --> 00:02:32.680
We'll get a lot of nice
flavor out of this.

00:02:32.680 --> 00:02:36.570
I also like how they
smell, which is weird.

00:02:36.570 --> 00:02:38.440
So we'll let that
kind of start off.

00:02:38.440 --> 00:02:42.500
Other ingredients in the
sauce itself are capers.

00:02:42.500 --> 00:02:44.920
Capers for me add a
saltiness, which I really

00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:48.690
like, without adding just a
handful or big pinch of salt.

00:02:48.690 --> 00:02:53.260
It actually adds a flavor, which
has its own again, salinity.

00:02:53.260 --> 00:02:55.550
We'll have sliced garlic.

00:02:55.550 --> 00:03:00.200
Again, the spicy component
to it is a piri piri chili.

00:03:00.200 --> 00:03:00.950
It's pretty spicy.

00:03:00.950 --> 00:03:02.420
It's a North African chili.

00:03:02.420 --> 00:03:04.680
This one happens to be dried.

00:03:04.680 --> 00:03:08.180
If for any reason
you can't find these,

00:03:08.180 --> 00:03:10.540
a chili flake is a
great substitution.

00:03:13.280 --> 00:03:15.640
What's fun again,
about this is if you're

00:03:15.640 --> 00:03:18.140
a fan of something spicy,
go ahead, get crazy with it,

00:03:18.140 --> 00:03:20.090
use a lot.

00:03:20.090 --> 00:03:23.750
But if you're kind of
timid about it, shy away.

00:03:23.750 --> 00:03:26.219
It's kind of making
what you want.

00:03:26.219 --> 00:03:28.260
What we're going to do is
add some sliced garlic.

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:38.760
And more or less
seeing fit to you.

00:03:38.760 --> 00:03:41.270
We're going to take a
couple of these piri piris.

00:03:41.270 --> 00:03:43.720
If you use these, make sure
to wash your hands after.

00:03:46.290 --> 00:03:48.455
Don't touch your face,
don't do anything else,

00:03:48.455 --> 00:03:49.555
just wash your hands.

00:03:52.959 --> 00:03:54.500
And with these, I'm
just about adding

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:57.475
or I'm going to add
four or five of these.

00:03:57.475 --> 00:03:59.600
You can always add more,
it's hard to take it away,

00:03:59.600 --> 00:04:02.110
so kind of a fun note with that.

00:04:04.890 --> 00:04:05.420
Capers.

00:04:05.420 --> 00:04:08.899
Capers themselves are going
to be the main salt component,

00:04:08.899 --> 00:04:10.940
so I actually enjoy quite
a few of that in there.

00:04:20.874 --> 00:04:23.290
And pretty soon you should be
able to start smelling this.

00:04:32.474 --> 00:04:34.140
IRENE NOKAN: How do
you go about finding

00:04:34.140 --> 00:04:36.665
quality shellfish like the
ones you're using here today?

00:04:36.665 --> 00:04:38.290
JASON HALVERSON:
There's a lot of trust

00:04:38.290 --> 00:04:40.760
that we have like
fish purveyors.

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:43.387
And you kind of just build this
trust on what they're getting

00:04:43.387 --> 00:04:44.720
and who they're getting it from.

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:50.470
And it's kind of like
a bad relationship

00:04:50.470 --> 00:04:52.697
where you always want
to trust that they're

00:04:52.697 --> 00:04:53.780
going to get you the best.

00:04:53.780 --> 00:04:55.280
And they usually
do, but those times

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:57.500
where if you run into
somebody that gives you just

00:04:57.500 --> 00:04:59.591
bad shellfish, it's really bad.

00:04:59.591 --> 00:05:00.340
Stay away from it.

00:05:00.340 --> 00:05:02.228
I tend not to try
to use them anymore.

00:05:05.341 --> 00:05:07.840
So as you guys can see, or I
don't know if you guys can see,

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:11.800
it's really starting
just to cook really fast.

00:05:11.800 --> 00:05:16.130
The onions are translucent,
the garlic has a smell.

00:05:16.130 --> 00:05:24.060
Next thing, we have a
little extra white wine.

00:05:24.060 --> 00:05:28.200
So white wine, you really want
something that's not sweet.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:29.311
I like acid wines.

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:35.070
You're starting to look at even
the style of like a Chardonnay

00:05:35.070 --> 00:05:37.526
or Sauvignon Blanc,
those kind of things.

00:05:37.526 --> 00:05:39.817
Again, just kind of trying
to stay away from sweetness.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:44.810
And what you're
going to let this do

00:05:44.810 --> 00:05:46.139
is now come up to a boil.

00:05:46.139 --> 00:05:48.680
Really what you're trying to do
is burn out that raw alcohol.

00:05:48.680 --> 00:05:48.980
All right.

00:05:48.980 --> 00:05:51.105
You're going to get that
flavor, you may get drunk,

00:05:51.105 --> 00:05:52.444
I don't know.

00:05:52.444 --> 00:05:54.360
But the idea is just to
burn out that alcohol.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:05:58.742
So that's up to a boil now.

00:05:58.742 --> 00:06:00.700
The last thing we're
going to add to this sauce

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:02.690
before we start on
the rest of it again,

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:06.959
is all the liquor from
cooking the mussels and clams.

00:06:06.959 --> 00:06:09.000
When you're cooking your
mussels and clams again,

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:09.624
save the juice.

00:06:09.624 --> 00:06:10.470
It's really good.

00:06:10.470 --> 00:06:13.790
One thing you want to do is,
before you cook your shellfish,

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:15.450
try to soak it in water.

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:18.034
Or let them kind of purge
out any extra sediment

00:06:18.034 --> 00:06:18.700
that's in there.

00:06:18.700 --> 00:06:20.600
Otherwise you're going to end
up with something really gritty.

00:06:20.600 --> 00:06:22.650
And after that, after
we cook it, we also

00:06:22.650 --> 00:06:25.750
strain it again just to
make sure there's no grit.

00:06:25.750 --> 00:06:26.785
So I'll add that in.

00:06:26.785 --> 00:06:27.691
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:06:27.691 --> 00:06:28.982
JASON HALVERSON: What was that?

00:06:28.982 --> 00:06:32.492
AUDIENCE: What did you add
to cook in [INAUDIBLE]?

00:06:32.492 --> 00:06:34.700
JASON HALVERSON: Just the
wine, or just the same wine

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:35.971
that we used for the sauce.

00:06:35.971 --> 00:06:37.220
AUDIENCE: Was there any water?

00:06:37.220 --> 00:06:38.720
JASON HALVERSON: No water.

00:06:38.720 --> 00:06:40.380
Water acts for me
like it's always

00:06:40.380 --> 00:06:42.250
great to have and use
when you're cooking.

00:06:42.250 --> 00:06:43.960
It's kind of that,
it dilutes flavors.

00:06:43.960 --> 00:06:46.210
So you're going to have to
cook something a little bit

00:06:46.210 --> 00:06:49.651
longer just to make that happen.

00:06:49.651 --> 00:06:53.290
So again, literally, we're going
to let this come up to a boil.

00:06:53.290 --> 00:06:54.250
We'll turn it down.

00:06:54.250 --> 00:06:56.583
You just really want to let
these flavors come together.

00:06:56.583 --> 00:06:59.370
It takes about 10, 15 minutes
in a batch about this size.

00:06:59.370 --> 00:07:02.440
So give it a taste and make
sure it's what you want.

00:07:02.440 --> 00:07:05.430
The next thing we're going
to make is the pasta.

00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:08.310
So anybody ever made pasta?

00:07:08.310 --> 00:07:08.990
Anybody?

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:09.490
Yeah?

00:07:09.490 --> 00:07:10.200
A lot of fun.

00:07:10.200 --> 00:07:12.790
I love making pasta.

00:07:12.790 --> 00:07:14.590
The pasta we're going
to make, no eggs.

00:07:14.590 --> 00:07:15.090
OK.

00:07:15.090 --> 00:07:18.790
So really kind of a hand
rolled style pasta dough.

00:07:18.790 --> 00:07:21.340
What we have here in the
bowl, two different flours.

00:07:21.340 --> 00:07:25.091
We have Double 00 flour
and Extra Fancy Durum.

00:07:25.091 --> 00:07:26.590
So the combination,
what you'll see,

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:29.730
just makes for a different
texture of pasta.

00:07:29.730 --> 00:07:31.890
We like this one really
dense, because what

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:34.230
happens when you cook it,
especially in the sauce,

00:07:34.230 --> 00:07:36.400
it starts to absorb the sauce.

00:07:36.400 --> 00:07:39.540
Just kind of making
things taste better.

00:07:39.540 --> 00:07:43.090
With that what we have here
is a combination of water,

00:07:43.090 --> 00:07:46.080
just like we talked
about, and squid ink.

00:07:46.080 --> 00:07:48.460
Squid ink, not a lot of
flavor necessarily in it.

00:07:48.460 --> 00:07:50.710
You're not gonna necessarily
get this super brininess,

00:07:50.710 --> 00:07:52.260
but you definitely
get this color,

00:07:52.260 --> 00:07:54.885
which kind of associate with.

00:07:54.885 --> 00:07:56.760
More so just going to
add all these together.

00:07:56.760 --> 00:07:58.176
IRENE NOKAN: Is
there a reason why

00:07:58.176 --> 00:08:01.400
you prefer to add the
squid ink with the pasta

00:08:01.400 --> 00:08:02.467
versus in the sauce?

00:08:02.467 --> 00:08:04.508
JASON HALVERSON: I like,
that's a great question.

00:08:06.815 --> 00:08:08.440
First and foremost,
when I'm eating it,

00:08:08.440 --> 00:08:10.830
I've had bad experiences
where I eat it as a sauce,

00:08:10.830 --> 00:08:14.310
and then for some reason I
smile and I have black teeth.

00:08:14.310 --> 00:08:16.210
Not so hot.

00:08:16.210 --> 00:08:18.810
It gets kind of weird.

00:08:18.810 --> 00:08:22.660
I look like that
guy, which is no fun.

00:08:22.660 --> 00:08:26.550
So it actually kind of helps
tame the whole I guess,

00:08:26.550 --> 00:08:30.520
identity of the squid ink.

00:08:30.520 --> 00:08:32.128
So I'm going to
kind of cheat here.

00:08:32.128 --> 00:08:34.929
We're going to use
the KitchenAid.

00:08:34.929 --> 00:08:36.470
We're going to start
with the paddle.

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:43.280
I don't know if you
guys can see it.

00:08:43.280 --> 00:08:46.421
More so just to kind of
bring the dough together.

00:08:46.421 --> 00:08:48.170
IRENE NOKAN: And for
those who don't know,

00:08:48.170 --> 00:08:51.030
what is Double 00 flour,
and where can you get that?

00:08:51.030 --> 00:08:53.446
JASON HALVERSON: You can get
it, most of these ingredients

00:08:53.446 --> 00:08:56.630
you'll be able to find really
easily at a Whole Foods readily

00:08:56.630 --> 00:08:57.130
available.

00:08:57.130 --> 00:09:00.526
It's an extra milled flour.

00:09:00.526 --> 00:09:03.700
Its has a different gluten
and different absorption

00:09:03.700 --> 00:09:05.520
rate than something
like an AP flour.

00:09:05.520 --> 00:09:07.860
You can absolutely
make it with that,

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:10.420
this just helps with
again, the textures,

00:09:10.420 --> 00:09:11.740
the density, things like that.

00:09:14.750 --> 00:09:17.480
So let's see if I can't--

00:09:17.480 --> 00:09:18.992
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:18.992 --> 00:09:21.200
JASON HALVERSON: I've also
found it at a Whole Foods.

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:23.050
Obviously we have our
own purveyor for it,

00:09:23.050 --> 00:09:26.340
but for the small amounts,
instead of buying a huge jar,

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:30.397
I've definitely seen it
at a Whole Foods for sure.

00:09:30.397 --> 00:09:32.730
IRENE NOKAN: And for those
who didn't hear the question,

00:09:32.730 --> 00:09:34.700
it was where do you
source the squid ink.

00:09:39.110 --> 00:09:41.610
JASON HALVERSON:
Hand that to you.

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:42.271
This is great.

00:09:45.319 --> 00:09:47.610
In case you guys are wondering,
this is Ryan over here.

00:09:47.610 --> 00:09:52.623
He usually tells me what to
do, so this is kind of nice.

00:09:55.990 --> 00:09:57.990
IRENE NOKAN: Is he with
you in the kitchen, too?

00:09:57.990 --> 00:09:59.460
JASON HALVERSON: He's usually
yelling at me in the kitchen.

00:09:59.460 --> 00:10:00.210
IRENE NOKAN: Yeah?

00:10:00.210 --> 00:10:04.420
JASON HALVERSON: But, so
really what's going to happen

00:10:04.420 --> 00:10:06.620
here is this dough's
going to come together.

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:08.800
If anybody, again,
has made dough--

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:11.420
I'm going to try to
churn it somehow,

00:10:11.420 --> 00:10:13.922
I'm looking at the
screen back there--

00:10:13.922 --> 00:10:15.630
usually a dough will
come together really

00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:17.730
fast with this one with no egg.

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:20.000
You really actually want
it as dry as possible.

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.060
It becomes really difficult to
work with when it's super dry,

00:10:24.060 --> 00:10:25.750
but the outcome is way better.

00:10:25.750 --> 00:10:27.310
Obviously if you
add too much water,

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:32.709
it just becomes really
elasticky and kind of a mess.

00:10:32.709 --> 00:10:35.250
What's fun about these pastas
is they hold their shape really

00:10:35.250 --> 00:10:40.140
well when the texture's right.

00:10:40.140 --> 00:10:43.050
So that's kind of what
we're looking for.

00:10:43.050 --> 00:10:45.654
So this is actually going
to take a little while.

00:10:45.654 --> 00:10:46.570
It will come together.

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:48.267
That's what it does.

00:10:48.267 --> 00:10:50.100
But to kind of move
with it, what we've done

00:10:50.100 --> 00:10:51.775
is actually made
the pasta itself.

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:56.862
It's a nice big
black sheet of pasta.

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:03.340
Started this week,
we're fortunate to have

00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:05.950
a pasta machine,
which makes working

00:11:05.950 --> 00:11:09.020
with pasta a little bit easier.

00:11:09.020 --> 00:11:11.890
And what we've done, we've just
rolled it out into a sheet.

00:11:16.590 --> 00:11:21.160
So rolled out to say, just
over an eighth of an inch.

00:11:21.160 --> 00:11:24.320
And what we do is we
just cut little squares.

00:11:24.320 --> 00:11:24.876
It's fun.

00:11:27.750 --> 00:11:29.340
One of the reasons
I like making pasta

00:11:29.340 --> 00:11:33.390
is there are so many different
shapes you can kind of go with.

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:35.640
Even if it's not really a
shape, you made it yourself,

00:11:35.640 --> 00:11:37.189
so it's kind of cool.

00:11:37.189 --> 00:11:37.730
It's organic.

00:11:43.115 --> 00:11:44.773
So just cutting
into little squares.

00:11:49.864 --> 00:11:51.280
And then what we're
going to do is

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:52.738
we're going to use
a little gnocchi

00:11:52.738 --> 00:12:01.944
board to kind of
make a shape, which

00:12:01.944 --> 00:12:03.110
you can find at most places.

00:12:03.110 --> 00:12:07.550
William Sonoma, Sur la Table,
Amazon, all those places

00:12:07.550 --> 00:12:09.159
you can find them.

00:12:09.159 --> 00:12:11.700
As you guys can tell, this one's
been used just a little bit,

00:12:11.700 --> 00:12:13.621
makes a lot of pasta.

00:12:13.621 --> 00:12:14.620
You get a lot of ridges.

00:12:14.620 --> 00:12:18.290
You get ridges out of this,
you can start to make shapes.

00:12:18.290 --> 00:12:21.610
So what we do is with that
being somewhat of a square,

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:23.950
we'll aim at rolling
from corner to corner.

00:12:23.950 --> 00:12:26.000
So what you're going
to do is push and kind

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.100
of roll, which is
fun for the shape.

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:30.814
So push and roll.

00:12:30.814 --> 00:12:32.480
And that's kind of
what you end up with.

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:33.480
I got lucky on that one.

00:12:36.044 --> 00:12:37.960
IRENE NOKAN: You made
that look fancy so fast.

00:12:37.960 --> 00:12:39.026
JASON HALVERSON: I did.

00:12:39.026 --> 00:12:40.470
I got lucky.

00:12:40.470 --> 00:12:43.559
So really again, you can
make all sorts of shapes.

00:12:43.559 --> 00:12:45.850
If it comes to being where
you don't have one of these,

00:12:45.850 --> 00:12:47.350
it's not going to
be something where

00:12:47.350 --> 00:12:48.440
you can't make this pasta.

00:12:48.440 --> 00:12:51.950
If you have a counter, which
I hope most of you guys do,

00:12:51.950 --> 00:12:56.320
you're making the pasta somehow,
roll it straight on the board.

00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:58.350
You're not gonna
really lose much.

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:00.290
It's just kind of fun.

00:13:00.290 --> 00:13:03.280
Really just kind of build, I
guess, your repertoire of pasta

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:05.640
making.

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:06.590
AUDIENCE: Use a fork.

00:13:06.590 --> 00:13:07.756
JASON HALVERSON: Use a fork.

00:13:07.756 --> 00:13:08.360
Absolutely.

00:13:08.360 --> 00:13:11.890
If you guys didn't hear, the
suggestion was to use a fork.

00:13:11.890 --> 00:13:13.190
Italian grandmothers use forks.

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:15.731
I love Italian grandmothers,
and they make really good pasta.

00:13:15.731 --> 00:13:19.670
So absolutely go for it.

00:13:19.670 --> 00:13:20.960
But that's what you can do.

00:13:20.960 --> 00:13:23.422
What's fun is in the
case of what you'll

00:13:23.422 --> 00:13:25.880
see with this dish is if you're
going to have friends over,

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:27.796
you can make most of
this dish all in advance.

00:13:27.796 --> 00:13:29.700
It becomes really easy.

00:13:29.700 --> 00:13:31.810
Almost feel like a
Sara Lee or someone

00:13:31.810 --> 00:13:34.950
like that trying to tell
you guys how to do this.

00:13:34.950 --> 00:13:40.130
But feel free to make the pasta
head and just to be ready.

00:13:40.130 --> 00:13:42.850
So with this pasta, we'll have
a pot of boiling water, which

00:13:42.850 --> 00:13:43.933
we don't have set up here.

00:13:43.933 --> 00:13:46.070
We made pasta already.

00:13:46.070 --> 00:13:48.770
Make sure it's up to a boil,
lightly seasoned with salt.

00:13:48.770 --> 00:13:50.560
And the reason I
say lightly seasoned

00:13:50.560 --> 00:13:53.000
is because the sauce itself
is going to have salt. Again,

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:54.374
you can always
add salt, you just

00:13:54.374 --> 00:13:56.940
don't want to hit that point
of something being salty.

00:13:56.940 --> 00:13:59.050
You'll boil it for
about three minutes.

00:13:59.050 --> 00:14:01.320
You'll still have a little
bit, it'll be al dente.

00:14:01.320 --> 00:14:04.340
You'll still have a
little bit of a bite.

00:14:04.340 --> 00:14:08.340
Just kind of adding to the
right texture for this dish, so

00:14:08.340 --> 00:14:11.030
basically, after you're
done blanching the pasta.

00:14:11.030 --> 00:14:12.070
See where we're at here.

00:14:12.070 --> 00:14:14.030
This is what it looks like.

00:14:14.030 --> 00:14:16.630
It's going to be a
nice, sturdy pasta.

00:14:16.630 --> 00:14:21.060
It's really, it's what it is.

00:14:21.060 --> 00:14:23.790
We'll start that.

00:14:23.790 --> 00:14:25.300
Get this out of the way.

00:14:25.300 --> 00:14:28.200
Again, being a shellfish
pasta, what we're going to do

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:33.190
is I'm going to show you guys
all the seafoods that we use.

00:14:33.190 --> 00:14:33.910
I love seafood.

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:35.910
Anybody here
allergic to seafood?

00:14:35.910 --> 00:14:36.628
I hope not.

00:14:39.560 --> 00:14:40.310
Might not like me.

00:14:46.550 --> 00:14:49.852
So again, to start
mussels and clams,

00:14:49.852 --> 00:14:51.060
we cooked them in white wine.

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:52.982
This is exactly what
we use for the sauce.

00:14:52.982 --> 00:14:54.440
Chef Deedee back
there actually did

00:14:54.440 --> 00:14:56.720
a great job of cooking the
pasta or the shellfish.

00:14:56.720 --> 00:14:58.080
Thank you for doing that.

00:14:58.080 --> 00:14:59.040
Appreciate it.

00:14:59.040 --> 00:15:02.770
So again, it's covered or a
hot pan, all the shellfish,

00:15:02.770 --> 00:15:03.849
white wine is covered.

00:15:03.849 --> 00:15:05.390
You're going to wait
until they open.

00:15:05.390 --> 00:15:05.890
That's it.

00:15:05.890 --> 00:15:07.820
They're ready to
go at that point.

00:15:07.820 --> 00:15:10.520
After that, we separated
it from the liquid,

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:13.540
and all we're going to do is
take them out of the shell.

00:15:13.540 --> 00:15:16.235
If they're not open, don't
try to fight them open.

00:15:16.235 --> 00:15:17.610
If everything else
is open, don't

00:15:17.610 --> 00:15:20.440
try to break them
open to get it out.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:24.120
That's not necessarily a good
sign of a good shellfish.

00:15:24.120 --> 00:15:25.310
So that was the mussels.

00:15:25.310 --> 00:15:28.701
The clams, the exact same thing.

00:15:28.701 --> 00:15:30.200
Just kind of pulling
these guys out.

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:41.850
There you go.

00:15:41.850 --> 00:15:44.896
So we have that.

00:15:44.896 --> 00:15:46.770
Don't know why I did
this, but everything can

00:15:46.770 --> 00:15:48.430
kind of go in the same bowl.

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:50.388
It's all going to go in
the same place anyways.

00:15:53.320 --> 00:15:55.765
So then after that
we have our calamari.

00:15:55.765 --> 00:15:56.600
I love calamari.

00:15:56.600 --> 00:16:02.520
I can eat it fried,
baked, fried again.

00:16:02.520 --> 00:16:04.147
Love the stuff.

00:16:04.147 --> 00:16:05.980
And again with this,
make it as you see fit.

00:16:05.980 --> 00:16:07.910
With this we're going
to just do rings.

00:16:07.910 --> 00:16:10.950
It's pretty straightforward,
just cutting straight across.

00:16:18.650 --> 00:16:19.650
Nothing fancy with this.

00:16:19.650 --> 00:16:20.858
You can absolutely get fancy.

00:16:23.660 --> 00:16:27.330
Again, another way, too, if you
don't have calamari, calamari

00:16:27.330 --> 00:16:28.980
steak, you know what I mean.

00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:30.660
The possibilities
are pretty endless.

00:16:35.630 --> 00:16:39.890
Kind of based on what you
have, what you want to eat.

00:16:39.890 --> 00:16:42.320
We've done this version of a,
or this dish with a version

00:16:42.320 --> 00:16:44.910
of lobster before.

00:16:44.910 --> 00:16:47.356
That was super fancy,
especially for pasta.

