did that is because you have a
lot of raw ingredients, which

00:36:28.520 --> 00:36:30.228
is going to help bring
them all together.

00:36:30.228 --> 00:36:34.140
We got it to a certain
point where it's there,

00:36:34.140 --> 00:36:36.380
or that it actually
started to come together.

00:36:36.380 --> 00:36:38.909
And then you're going to
want to just kind of check

00:36:38.909 --> 00:36:39.450
the moisture.

00:36:39.450 --> 00:36:41.740
But as you can tell
it's dough now.

00:36:41.740 --> 00:36:43.240
What we try to do
with the hook then

00:36:43.240 --> 00:36:48.650
is use the hook to kind
of knead the dough.

00:36:48.650 --> 00:36:50.960
Kind of starting all the
glutens and to make the dough

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:54.790
come together, to give
it some structure.

00:36:54.790 --> 00:36:56.660
For this dough, it does
take a little while

00:36:56.660 --> 00:37:02.140
to come together, which
makes the dough what it is.

00:37:02.140 --> 00:37:04.650
If it was super, we could
add a ton of water in here,

00:37:04.650 --> 00:37:06.710
it would come together
in two seconds.

00:37:06.710 --> 00:37:11.139
But then you're going to have
this really soft pasta that's

00:37:11.139 --> 00:37:13.430
more like an overcooked noodle
before you even cook it.

00:37:13.430 --> 00:37:17.467
So that's kind of how
the two work together.

00:37:21.862 --> 00:37:23.570
AUDIENCE: If you don't
have a KitchenAid,

00:37:23.570 --> 00:37:25.196
