00:38:09.916 --> 00:38:12.030
It's two ingredients,
flours and water.

00:38:12.030 --> 00:38:14.700
And pretty straightforward
from there.

00:38:14.700 --> 00:38:16.450
IRENE NOKAN: And can
you talk a little bit

00:38:16.450 --> 00:38:22.340
about the advantages of fresh
pasta versus a dried pasta?

00:38:22.340 --> 00:38:24.510
JASON HALVERSON: I'm
not biased either.

00:38:24.510 --> 00:38:29.120
So fresh pasta,
we'll start here.

00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:31.220
Dried pasta, generally,
we're buying it.

00:38:31.220 --> 00:38:32.470
I don't have to make anything.

00:38:32.470 --> 00:38:34.310
It's kind of nice.

00:38:34.310 --> 00:38:37.280
What's really actually nice
about dry pastas for me is

00:38:37.280 --> 00:38:41.660
there's a little bit
more time cooking.

00:38:41.660 --> 00:38:44.100
So for me, if there is more
time to cook something,

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.780
I get to do a little bit more
in terms of flavor and texture.

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:49.190
And you're going to notice
those kind of things.

00:38:49.190 --> 00:38:53.080
So if I had grandma's
tomato sauce,

00:38:53.080 --> 00:38:58.679
I might cook the dried pasta for
a little while 3/4 of the time

00:38:58.679 --> 00:39:00.220
that it's supposed
to say on the box.

00:39:00.220 --> 00:39:03.010
I might take and add
in some grandma's sauce

00:39:03.010 --> 00:39:04.367
and use that to cook it more.

00:39:04.367 --> 00:39:05.950
All of a sudden, my
pasta has absorbed

00:39:05.950 --> 00:39:10.760
more of that sauce as opposed
to water, butter, and cheese.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:13.220
So that's kind of
one huge aspect.

00:39:13.220 --> 00:39:16.250
With fresh pasta, you
can manipulate it more so

00:39:16.250 --> 00:39:18.250
in the style of what it is.

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:20.510
Sheets, raviolis, things
like that, you can't really

00:39:20.510 --> 00:39:22.390
do that with a dried pasta.

00:39:22.390 --> 00:39:24.510
So there's a lot of things.

00:39:24.510 --> 00:39:26.590
It's really kind of
just due to the scenario

00:39:26.590 --> 00:39:27.610
in which you're in.

00:39:27.610 --> 00:39:28.080
IRENE NOKAN: Great.

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:28.580
Thanks.

